function findNearestRightNode(root, u) {
  if (!root) return null;

  const q = [root];

  while (q.length > 0) {
    const n = q.length;

    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
      const current = q.shift();

      if (current === u) {
        return i < n - 1 ? q[0] : null;
      }

      if (current.left) q.push(current.left);
      if (current.right) q.push(current.right);
    }
  }

  return null;
}
```

    The algorithm is based on level-order traversal (breadth-first search). We use a queue to traverse the tree nodes level by level.

1. We first check if the root is not null, otherwise, return null.
2. Initialize an empty queue and push the root node into it.
3. While the queue is not empty, we start a loop:
   1. Store the current size of the queue (n).
   2. Loop through the nodes in the current level (from 0 to n).
      1. Pop the front node from the queue (current).
      2. Check if this node is equal to the target node (u).
         1. If yes, return the next node in the queue if the current node is not the last node in the level. Otherwise, return null.
      3. If the current node has any left and/or right child, push them into the queue.
4. If we finished traversing the tree and didn't find any nearest node, return null.

